Is it possible to regulate systemic risks?
MILAN – Over the past two years, the global economy has been hit hard by financial instability and sudden market dynamics shifts.
Other such events are likely, as the global economy remains imbalanced in many ways, particularly in terms of sovereign debt and the structure of global demand.
Systemic risks are at the root of most crises and present a challenge for several reasons.
Firstly, they are not easy to detect with certainty and even more difficult to prove.
Next, predicting the precise moment of the tipping point (when the bubbles burst, when the markets are paralyzed, and when there is no more credit available) is, and will likely remain, beyond our analytical capabilities.
Finally, crises are strongly nonlinear events that occur without warning signs.
The periodic manifestations of instability impose a high social cost on those who are least responsible.
If this pattern were to repeat itself, it could undermine confidence in financial markets and regulatory authorities, a loss of confidence that could herald excessive regulations, state intervention, and a disengagement from globalization.
But the problem is even more severe.
The financial and economic crisis is transforming into a sovereign debt crisis of advanced countries.
Economic and financial imbalances can translate into a dangerous fiscal imbalance characterized by deteriorating tax revenues and increasing bailout expenditures.
The International Monetary Fund estimates that up to 75 percent of the "fiscal packages" of advanced economies include countercyclical non-discretionary measures.
The imbalances and undetected systemic risks mean that what appear to be prudent fiscal policies are not in fact so.
For example, Spain did not have a fiscal deficit at the start of the crisis.
But its revenues and expenditures were largely determined by a housing bubble related to very high levels of debt.
An extreme fiscal imbalance can also lead to a "growth trap" in which fiscal consolidation has such a negative effect on growth that it cancels itself out.
Greece is likely a prime example of this.
In the end, the only exit is to reset the value of liabilities through restructuring or inflation.
If systemic risks can trigger such a sequential imbalance in cascades, sovereign states must be vigilant to the danger, capable of identifying the emergence of a systemic risk, and take corrective measures promptly.
New detailed legislative frameworks, focusing on capital requirements and leverage effects, transparency, ratings, and other sources of information, incentives, conflicts of interest, and limits on the size of financial institutions, consumer protection, and resolution mechanisms, will soon be adopted.
The hope is that these reforms will reduce the likelihood and severity of systemic risks.
But this will do nothing to address the problems of global imbalances and other factors contributing to and signaling instability.
In addition and complementing new legislative frameworks, a comprehensive system for monitoring systemic risks is necessary.
However, some politicians and top analysts believe that such a system, aimed at identifying and mitigating systemic risks, is futile.
The incomplete models of risk dynamics and a globally complex and constantly mutating financial system make it, according to them, either impossible or so prone to error that the effort would be futile.
Asset bubbles are almost impossible to identify without error.
If the skeptics are right, then we must accept that we will periodically find ourselves in a situation of financial and fiscal instability without being able to predict it in advance.
We should also then accept a much more prudent fiscal policy than the one we deemed necessary just three years ago.
In the field of statistics and decision-making under uncertainty, errors are inevitable.
There are two types of errors: one consists of rejecting a true proposition and the other is accepting a false proposition.
Let's call them RQV (rejected when true) and AQF (accepted when false).
The question can be put in these terms: in the context of detecting and responding to systemic risks, which of these two types of errors is likely to have the highest cost?
The opponents of prudent risk monitoring of systemic risks have two different positions.
One of them is that the AQF error will not occur, because there is no reliable sign heralding a potentially increasing instability.
Looking for such a sign is a waste of time.
The instability occurs instantly.
But this position appears fallacious.
For example, during the 2008 crisis, some analysts did issue warnings and some investors took note.
However, it must be admitted that these warnings may not have been sufficient to be irrefutable and they certainly did not predict the point of breakdown.
They were nevertheless unmistakable signs.
The second point is that there are indeed signs, but they are so unreliable that taking action would do more harm than good.
This view implies that the probable cost of AQF is higher than that of RQV, because there are many false positive elements and/or the remedy is worse than the problem.
There is no doubt that there are costs associated with AQF errors.
But RQV is also costly, as we have seen, so the negative aggregated effect of a reaction to false positives (AQF) must be significant to be convincing.
I am not convinced, for my part.
There may be a deeper tendency towards openness.
Be it in business or investments, choices are constantly made under conditions of uncertainty and errors are frequent.
The default position of decision-makers in advanced countries seems to be, on the contrary, that proactive and preemptive measures require a high level of certainty, linked to the deeply ingrained belief that financial markets are stable and self-regulating.
If one thinks that market instability is rare, then it is reasonable to refrain from acting unless there are good reasons to do so.
But in the light of past experiences, the idea that the global financial system is only exceptionally unstable or on a slippery slope is at best debatable.
Basing ourselves on new theories and experiences, we could eventually conclude that political responses to systemic risks are impossible to design and that the cost of AQF errors is higher than the cost of RQV errors.
But we should at least try this experiment, and in doing so, give responsibilities to a new institution, or an existing one, that has access to relevant information, possesses sharp analytical skills both at the financial and macroeconomic levels, and is relatively insulated from conflicts of interest.
Its analysis should be made public and could thus influence perceptions of systemic risks and market behavior, thereby enhancing the system's ability to regulate itself.
